http://www.gideononline.com


re: Leptospirosis, fatal - Sri Lanka (02): (NW) 20110913.2785
-------------------------------------------------------------
The following background data on leptospirosis in Sri Lanka have been
abstracted from the Gideon web application (Gideon
http://www.gideononline.com/) and e-book series. [1,2]

Time and Place:
Leptospirosis was 1st reported in Sri Lanka in 1953.
- Most cases are reported in Moneragala, Ampara, Matara, Balle and the
Northwestern province.
- Highest risk is identified among paddy farmers and sugar cane
plantation workers.

Reported rates have increased dramatically since 2006 - see graph:
http://www.gideononline.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/Lepto-SriLanka.png
(graph tool tutorial at
http://www.GIDEONonline.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/Gideon-Graphs.pps).

Prevalence surveys:
- 13.5 percent of patients with febrile illness (Galle, 2007).

Seroprevalence surveys:
- 24.3 percent of patients with acute febrile illness (Kandy, 2010
publication)
- 27.1 percent of patients with febrile illness (Galle, 2007)
- 20.3 percent of cattle and 17.5 percent of rodents (Kandy, 2011
publication).

References:
1. Berger SA. Infectious Diseases of Sri Lanka, 2011. 364 pp, 71
graphs, 1063 references. Gideon e-books,
http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/country/infectious-diseases-of-sri-lanka/
2. Berger SA. Leptospirosis: Global Status, 2011. 148 pp, 165 graphs,
834 references. Gideon e-books,
http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/disease/leptospirosis-global-status/

